==English==
=== Etymology ===
{{ME.}} ''[[quyksilver]]'' from Anglo Saxon ''[[cwicseolfor]]''. Literally "living silver" from its ability to move.  See [[quick]] in the sense of living.

=== Noun ===
'''quicksilver'''
# the metal [[mercury]]
#*The rogue fled from me like '''quicksilver''' - Shakespeare, ''Henry IV part 2'', II-iv
#*'''1820:''' Thou hast '''quicksilver''' in the veins of thee to a certainty. - [[w:Walter Scott|Walter Scott]], ''The Abbot''
# {{colloquial}} an amalgam of mercury and tin applied to the backs of mirrors, [[quicksilvering]]

